  abstract = {We conduct a comprehensive study on dropout galaxy candidates at \$z\textbackslash sim 9-17\$ using the first 90 arcmin\$\^2\$ JWST/NIRCam images taken by the early release observations (ERO) and early release science (ERS) programs. With the JWST simulation images, we find that a number of foreground interlopers are selected with a weak photo-\$z\$ determination (\$\textbackslash Delta \textbackslash chi\^2{$>$}4\$). We thus carefully apply a secure photo-\$z\$ selection criterion (\$\textbackslash Delta \textbackslash chi\^2{$>$}9\$) and conventional color criteria with confirmations of the ERO NIRSpec spectroscopic redshifts, and obtain a total of 25 dropout galaxies at \$z\textbackslash sim 9-17\$, including two candidates at \$z\_\textbackslash mathrm\{phot\}=16.45\_\{-0.32\}\^\{+0.09\}\$ and \$16.66\_\{-0.34\}\^\{+1.86\}\$. We perform thorough comparisons of dropout galaxies found in our work with recent JWST studies, and conclude that our galaxy sample is reliable enough for statistical analyses. We derive the UV luminosity functions at \$z\textbackslash sim 9-17\$, and confirm that our UV luminosity functions at \$z\textbackslash sim 9\$ and \$12\$ agree with those determined by previous HST and JWST studies. The cosmic star-formation rate density decreases from \$z\textbackslash sim 9\$ to \$12\$, and perhaps to \$17\$, but the densities at \$z\textbackslash sim12-17\$ are higher than the constant star formation efficiency model. Interestingly, there are six bright galaxy candidates at \$z\textbackslash sim 11-17\$ with \$M\_\{\textbackslash rm UV\}{$<$}-19.5\$ whose stellar masses are very high, \$10\^\{8-9\} M\_\textbackslash odot\$. Because a majority (\$\textbackslash sim 70\textbackslash\%\$) of these galaxies shows no signatures of AGNs in their morphologies, the high cosmic star-formation rate densities and the existence of these stellar massive galaxies are explained by no suppression of star-formation by the UV background radiation at the pre-reionization epoch or an efficient UV radiation production by Population III-like star formation.},
